Week 1: Single-Machine Token Bucket Rate Limiter Library
Objective
Build a rate limiting library that implements the token bucket algorithm. Users should be able to check if a request is allowed based on their rate limit configuration.
What is Token Bucket?
A bucket holds tokens up to a maximum capacity. Tokens refill at a constant rate (e.g., 10 tokens per second). When someone requests access, they need one token. If the bucket has a token, request is allowed and the token is consumed. If empty, request is denied. Over time, tokens come back and more requests are allowed again.
Test Cases
Test 1: First request succeeds (bucket starts full)

Bucket capacity: 10 tokens
Refill rate: 1 token per second
Call tryAcquire() once at time T=0
Expected result: true

Test 2: Bucket depletes after multiple requests

Bucket capacity: 2 tokens
Refill rate: 0.1 tokens per second
Call tryAcquire() three times in quick succession at T=0
Expected: first two return true, third returns false

Test 3: Tokens refill over time

Bucket capacity: 5 tokens
Refill rate: 1 token per second
Call tryAcquire() 5 times at T=0 — all succeed (bucket empties)
Call tryAcquire() again at T=0 — fails (no tokens)
Advance time to T=2 seconds
Call tryAcquire() 2 times — both succeed (2 tokens refilled)
Call tryAcquire() again — fails (only had 2, used 2)

Test 4: Burst tolerance (quiet client suddenly fires requests)

Bucket capacity: 100 tokens
Refill rate: 10 tokens per second
Client is quiet for 5 seconds
At T=5 seconds, client fires 100 requests rapidly
Expected: all 100 succeed (bucket is full)
Request 101 fails

Test 5: Multiple clients don't interfere with each other

Create two separate rate limiters with same config: capacity 2, refill rate 1/sec
Client A uses 3 tokens at T=0 — first 2 succeed, third fails
Client B uses 3 tokens at T=0 — first 2 succeed, third fails
Each client's bucket is independent


